docs.abstract: When she has free time, Claire Sprouse makes a point of supporting small local businesses, since she runs one herself.
docs.snippet: When she has free time, Claire Sprouse makes a point of supporting small local businesses, since she runs one herself.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2016, Claire Sprouse moved from San Francisco, where she had become an outspoken activist on sustainability in bars, to New York in an effort to continue her mission here. Three years later, she opened Hunky Dory, her eclectic and earthy restaurant and bar in Crown Heights, Brooklyn, which focuses on minimizing waste and features herbs and fruit from a community garden in its cocktails and dishes.

headline.main: How a Restaurateur and Activist Spends Her Sundays
headline.print_headline: Activist Explores Inner and Outer Space

docs.abstract: Stepan Svetlov hasn’t set foot in Belarus for two years. But his social media profile is now a lodestar for demonstrators back home.
docs.snippet: Stepan Svetlov hasn’t set foot in Belarus for two years. But his social media profile is now a lodestar for demonstrators back home.
docs.lead_paragraph: WARSAW — Stepan Svetlov’s computer sits on a desk in Warsaw, nearly 300 miles from Minsk, the capital of Belarus. But when Belarusians poured into the streets in the hours and days after President Aleksandr G. Lukashenko fraudulently claimed a re-election victory on Aug. 9, it was thanks in no small part to Mr. Svetlov, 22, and his computer.

headline.main: The 22-Year-Old Coordinating Protests in Belarus, From a Small Office in Poland
headline.print_headline: Stoking the Lingering Protests in Belarus From a Tiny Office in Warsaw

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The F.B.I. has not seen evidence of a “coordinated national voter fraud effort,” its director, Christopher A. headline.main: F.B.I. Director Sees No Evidence of National Mail Voting Fraud Effort

docs.abstract: Some Black residents of Kenosha, upended by the police shooting of Jacob Blake, weren’t convinced that an election would solve the problem.

docs.lead_paragraph: KENOSHA, Wis. — Gerald Holmes, a forklift operator from Kenosha, Wis., was so passionate about the importance of the election four years ago that he drove people without rides to the polls. But this year, Mr. Holmes says he is not even planning to vote himself.

headline.main: Efforts to Channel Protests Into More Votes Face Challenges in Kenosha
